<subSubSection pageId="52" pageNumber="53" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Tetraserica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tetraserica breviforceps" order="Coleoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviforceps">Tetraserica breviforceps</taxonomicName>
sp. n. differs from all other 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Tetraserica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tetraserica" order="Coleoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Tetraserica</taxonomicName>
species with its short parameres and very short median phallobasal lamina, and by the left paramere having a robust (nearly half as long as paramere), subsphaerical, and apically convex dorsal lobe at its base.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="52" pageNumber="53" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="52" pageNumber="53">The name of the new species (noun in apposition) is derived from the combined Latin words brevis (short) and forceps, with reference to the short parameres.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
